segments.text: He said there were millionaires in this country.
There were lots of guys that had over a million dollars.
That's quite common.
And I couldn't understand it, you know, because that term was unknown.
Millionaires.
Just to be a millionaire is a kind of a professional, so I might say.
You know, that was unknown.
We had some rich people, especially old families that had lots of land.
and some industrialists, but they were not referred to as millionaires per se, like somebody can be a millionaire and not have a job.
Yes, that's true.
You know, per se, he's just a millionaire.
So that was, naturally I wanted to find out all I could about this country, naturally.
Curiosity was tremendous.
And I wasn't going to find out anything by being shipped back or
You know, nobody was going to tell me any more than I already knew in prison camp.
So I felt that was another thing I, all these many reasons that I gave myself for escaping, you know, why I was doing this.
I was just agonized over it for months and months and months.
And I wanted to find what this common sense was that,
that Germans seem to lack from WW1.
Yes.
Yes.
I'll tell you a funny story about, Candy has heard it so many times.
I'll tell a story where Mercury's Law, with the chorus girls from Reno that turned out to be, one of them turned out to be a German countess, according to her story.
And I know she was German, but I could tell by the accent and her behavior when she would order, when she would have dark bread and German bread for breakfast.
Yeah.
And it was...
In a sense, she did not suspect me of anything other than that I was an American ski instructor.
But she must have sensed something because she did like me better than the other guys.
So there was some attraction there.
And fortunately nothing, it was no danger to me because she was, actually she moved in better circles.
She had more income than I had.
I couldn't keep up with her partying.
She could pass better.
She would speak in her accent and everybody thought it was cute.

And that used to upset me because the Austrian ski instructors that would come over, they could speak horrible English and the girls would just laugh and laugh and they would think they were the cutest thing since you know what.
And I had to carefully pick my words.
I probably was considered dull because I couldn't
speak fast enough, compete with these guys who were yodeling and, you know, they were just turning on their charm.
And I couldn't read.
It's very hard.
That, I think, is difficult.
You lose your charm as a fugitive.
Because you haven't got the spontaneity that you need to be a professor.
I must have been considered dull so many times that
You know, what is the matter with them?
Didn't you think something was going to happen?
You were, at that point, a very confident, a super confident person.
Remember what Cheryl said?
Cheryl, my daughter, was 16 when I met all her little girlfriends over at the summer parties.
And what she told you the other night, what she thought, she had no idea.
Yeah, they thought it was something strange.
They thought you were strange.
Yeah.
But then, you know...
When all the friends would come over, they'd look at him and they'd say, who is this guy?
Where did he come from?
Where did you meet this guy?
This was Palo Alto, California.
They had a short history, so it was kind of... Usually because everybody talks at least about their school days.
See, I couldn't even talk about my school days.
But his accent at that time was a little heavier.
But very few people called me on it, though.
Very few people.
Like the guys I worked for.
I worked for the Clark brothers.
They never said a word about my accent.
We were even wearing Tyrolean hats.
We were still involved those days.
In the 50s.
Very few people would call me on it.
And if they did, then I would
really slow down and check my, what I said more, be more careful.

I used to correct him about his pronunciation, and then I, I felt that I was doing, it wasn't his problem, it was my problem, because you should not be correcting someone's grammar, so then I just stopped doing it, and then I didn't think about it anymore.
And now, years later, he doesn't do that, or at least .
It doesn't bother you?
No.
I'm absolutely astonished at his grasp of the English language, his range, and sometimes when he mispronounces things, I think it's delightful.
It's not .
People are very forgiving.
Very forgiving.
Amazing.
Like I say, these girls, the more accent you had in those ski resorts, the better they liked you.
And here I could have had an accent and I couldn't use it, you might say.
You could have charmed the... Yeah.
So I had to play the, I don't know what I played, you know, I just had to be, I didn't know.

the distance between you, that you hadn't merged somehow, is it?

And then I guess I got into it.
I didn't really want to press him for fear of finding out he was something.
I don't know.
We have a whole...

you teach me something and then you say, okay, now who's going to be the fastest?

young upcoming, he would have made it in politics or in the military either way.

It surprised me.
My whole family survived it.

My sister, yeah.

And here's some

Oh, I see.
Very talented artist.
What was his name again?
My mother and father raised my sister's two girls.
So they had another family, so to speak.
Because my sister stayed behind in Twightness for some reason, unbeknownst to me.
It's in her letter.
Pardon?
It's in her letter.
Why she stayed there?
She worked on the farm.
And she gave up her two children to your parents?
Yes, to get him over the border.
Somehow they didn't get her out for some reason.
What happened to Herbert?
Herbert got out.

I believe so.
That's the impression I got, that Herbert got out first, and then my sister got out last.

She's the youngest, his youngest niece.
All right, of these two that your parents raised.
Yeah.
That the two girls were smuggled out by,
I have pictures of them.
with the two babies.

There was when I was still
On the run.
I was just a student.
I remember visiting him in the hospital.
So he was put into the labor, on a labor crew.
My father was put on the labor crew, on the railroad, you know, the labor gang that goes out and checks the ties when he was probably 16 years old.

Oh, it was the Russians that put him on the labor crew.
Yeah.
Got it.
The Russians put him on the labor crews.

I don't know the details of his escape.
But once he got out, then he managed to get my mother and everybody else, two nieces out, and last, my sister.
And I knew he was the only one that could do it.
A guy like me, my age, you go into the nearest labor camp, no matter what.
Absolutely.
What's your story is, you know?
Older guys, he was probably old enough that they let him go.
And young, old women, they were okay, you know.
But guys, army age, it's just... You know, right to a labor.
Yeah.
Let me ask you about the, we've gone through the camps, just shifted from camp to camp in a routine way.
How did you find out when it was time to be shifted to another camp?
Did rumors go through the camp, or all of a sudden they blew the whistles and everyone said, line up, get your stuff, we're moving to another place?
It was announced, it was posted, I believe.
Only certain people went?
Yeah, it was always a selective process, which we never could figure out what it was.
We didn't seem to, I mean, we felt that it could be something else.

oh yes i just wondered if we never even thought about it much this i only found out later that there was some rhyme or reason behind it there were some big decisions being made somewhere else but we just thought it was routine because it's probably a good idea not to let him get too too too familiar with the with the area yes i think that's what i thought did you um
And as soon as you moved to a new camp, you immediately made another camp translator?
Usually it turned out that way, in most cases, because, like I say, very few people spoke as well as I did.
Yes, I can see.
I mean, they always had somebody who could speak a little English, but they didn't have the command that I had, so they always took me in.
Even if they had another translator, they'd say, come on along, you know, just in case.
And then gave me the job of translating those people articles.
And the Wehrmacht, their daily news bulletin or something, the battles and various fronts and all that.
And you were never accused of being pro-American, anti-American, pro-Nazi, anti?
I don't know.
I'm not sure about that, to be honest with you.
I'm not sure, because I don't know.
There were some, a lot of things were going on, and there were some rumors, but nothing was really personal that I know of.
And I just kind of tried to stay out of this when it got political, this area.
We left these guys alone, these hard Nazi guys.
And they stayed too.
I was in my camps.
Did you have anybody in the camps from the 999th penal battalion that was with the Africa Corps?
It was the 999.
What was that?
They were some special...
It was a penal, a disciplinary battalion attached to the Africa Corps.
And many of them were anti-Nazis, many of them were criminals, many of them were, you know, they formed a unit called the 999.
When you got to Lawrenceburg, did you ever participate on the camp newspaper, Lagosaito, or anything like that?
Well, I did the translation, but

uh and read the paper but i don't i don't publish anything no because the every campaign usually had a newspaper yeah i remember publishing one story once and they wanted more but i didn't know anymore it was the story about the okay guy where the where the origin of okay came from and i don't know where i read that but it's supposed to came from
come from Otto Krause or something.

Krause.

How did the other prisoners react to the end of the war?
April, May 1st, May 2nd, May 3rd.
Everybody kept to themselves.
It was a shell shock.
But they knew the war had been going badly.
Couldn't have been it.
It wasn't, well, some of them, they wouldn't really, they didn't want to leave.
They couldn't leave because things must have changed really fast, like from the time I left, which wasn't all that long, and it was absolute quiet.
There were no battles ranging when I left.
Right.
In Germany, probably.
In Germany, or even anywhere else.
No, it's true.
We didn't hit the beaches until 44.
See, it was all in a relatively short time.
There were no big battles that Stalingrad had after those battles.
They couldn't believe it.

Just military personnel?
Never.
I would think they were special units, like the SS or something.
But these are strictly... Military personnel.
Military, army, kind of...
If anything, we had a mixture of career.
Army guys, officers, and I'd say 20% or so, 23% were career.
Oh, I see.
I see.
And they were, you know, they were
maybe stubborn and very proud type, patriotic type, because they were trained to be that way, because they were a regular army.

The stories, we didn't, I'm trying to think when I heard, the stories about concentration camps,
first time in which camp it would be even if it wasn't.
It might have been afterwards.
They came out relatively late.
But the relationship between the guards and officers, the American officers and the other persons got worse from camp to camp.
started all on beautiful and then they were walking around with real strange expressions on their faces you know for us because we didn't know what and then

That would be my translation of a concentration camp, at least.

That's where it comes from.
So I figured a prison camp of people.

Yeah.

I could read.

know when people are upset about something.

Go back to the Soviet zone.

since I had no attorney or anybody to clarify this thing, because I was probably one of the few from that area.

five or six shots.

some Timbuktu.

I wasn't crazy.

Well, you get doubts, you know, when you...
all by yourself in some dark, miserable room, you know, what the heck am I doing here, you know?

Alive, yeah.

Oh, yes, I remember.

He doesn't belong anywhere.

Kinship for that time.

Outside the law.

Yes.
With his friends.
Yes.

At the beginning of September of 1945.

September.
September.
